      explain: "Choice \"B\" is correct. The $81.00 amount properly applies the FIFO cost flow approach within a periodic inventory system. Under a periodic inventory system, the cost of goods sold is calculated as follows: Beginning inventory + Purchases = Costs of goods available for sale — Ending inventory = Costs of goods sold To complete the calculation, the ending inventory value must be known. Since the problem states the company is using the FIFO (First In, First Out) method, the earliest units purchased are valued in the cost of goods sold first, which means that for ending inventory, the value would be based on the last quantities included in purchases. There are eight units in ending inventory. Purchase 3 was for three units at $12 each, and Purchase 2 was for six units at $10 each. All three units of Purchase 3 would be included in ending inventory, as well as five units of Purchase 2 (3 + 5 = 8 units). By multiplying the cost of each unit by the number of units, the ending inventory value can be determined to be $86: Description Units Unit price Total Purchase 2 5 $10 $50 Purchase 3 3 12 36 Ending inventory $86 By putting those values into the calculation, it can be determined that the ending costs of goods sold was $81 as shown below: Description Units Unit price Total January 1 balance 5 $7 $ 35 Purchase 1 4 9 36 Purchase 2 6 10 60 Purchase 3 3 12 36 Available 18 167 Less: Ending inventory (86) Cost of goods sold $ 81 Choice \"A\" is incorrect. The $105.00 amount incorrectly reflects a LIFO method as it considers the most recent costs first (LIFO method) to calculate cost of goods sold. Under LIFO, the remaining items in inventory at year-end would come from the beginning items in inventory and purchases. With eight units in inventory at year-end, that means five units would come from the beginning inventory balance (5 x $7 = $35) and the remaining three would come from Purchase 1 (3 x $9 = $27) for a total ending inventory balance of $62 ($35 + $27 = $62). Plugging that ending inventory balance amount into the periodic system costs of goods sold calculation gives an ending costs of goods sold amount of $105: Description Units Unit price Total January 1 balance 5 $7 $35 Purchase 1 4 9 36 Purchase 2 6 10 60 Purchase 3 3 12 36 Available 18 167 Less: Ending inventory (62) Cost of goods sold $105 Choice \"C\" is incorrect. The $92.80 amount appears to use a weighted average calculation as follows: Total cost of inventory available for sale $167 Total units available for sale /18 Cost per unit 9.28 10 units sold at $9.28 per unit $92.80 Choice \"D\" is incorrect. The $86.00 amount appears to reflect the value of ending inventory under a FIFO cost flow method as opposed to the value of cost of goods sold. 18 units were available for sale and 10 were sold, leaving eight in ending inventory. The value under FIFO is calculated by taking the eight units of ending inventory and assigning them to the latest purchases that were completed as follows: 3 units from Purchase 3 at $12 $36 5 units from Purchase 2 at $10 50 8 units in ending inventory at a total value $86"
