      q: "Bailey Co. changed the accounting for insurance expense from the cash basis to the accrual basis in Year 2. In January of Year 1, Bailey recorded insurance expense of $240,000 for the cash purchase of a four-year insurance policy. Bailey's Year 2 accrual- based financial statements should reflect which of the following journal entries at year-end?",
      choices: ["A$60,000 debit to insurance expense and a $60,000 credit to prepaid asset.", "A $60,000 debit to insurance expense, a $120,000 debit to prepaid asset, and a $180,000 credit to retained earnings.", "A$180,000 debit to insurance expense, a $120,000 credit to prepaid asset, and a $60,000 credit to retained earnings.", "A$180,000 debit to prepaid asset and a $180,000 credit to insurance expense."],
      answer: 1,
      explain: "Choice \"B\" is correct. A change from the cash basis method (non-GAAP) to the accrual basis method (GAAP) represents an error correction. When the error relates to a year not presented (as is the case here), the beginning retained earnings of the earliest period presented needs to be adjusted for the correction of the error. Under the cash- basis method of accounting, the entire $240,000 cash outlay for the four-year insurance policy would have been booked as an expense in Year 1. Under the accrual basis of accounting, the correct treatment is to record a prepaid asset of $240,000 (and cash outflow) when the policy is purchased, expensing $60,000 per year for four years while reducing the value of the prepaid asset. In Year 2, because the switch has been made to the accrual basis, the following accounts would be affected: e Insurance expense of $60,000 is debited to record the expense for Year 2 of the policy. e Aprepaid asset of $120,000 is debited to represent the third and fourth years that remain on the policy. e The retained earnings is credited to adjust for the net impact to Year 1 had the original $240,000 been recorded as a prepaid asset upon purchase, reduced by insurance expense of $60,000 for Year 1. The correct journal entry is as follows: DR Insurance expense $60,000 DR Prepaid asset 120,000 CR_ Retained earnings $180,000 Choice \"A\" is incorrect. Although a $60,000 charge to insurance expense is appropriate for Year 2, a debit of $120,000 (as opposed to a credit of $60,000) is what is needed to accurately reflect the remaining balance on the insurance policy as of the end of Year 2. Choice \"C\" is incorrect. The debit to insurance expense should be for $60,000, which represents the expense for the current year only. The $120,000 to the prepaid asset should be a debit to reflect the balance of two years remaining, and the credit to retained earnings should be $180,000 to offset the $240,000 expense from the first year. Choice \"D\" is incorrect. The balance in the prepaid asset account as of the end of Year 2 needs to reflect the amount remaining for the third and fourth years only."
