      choices: ["$48,000", "$60,000", "$36,000", "$54,000"],
      answer: 2,
      explain: "Choice \"C\" is correct. $54,000 prepaid expenses on the December 31, Year 1, balance sheet. On July 1, the company paid $72,000 for the annual (12 month) premium for the insurance policy. By December 31, half the annual policy expired. Therefore, $72,000 x 1/2 = $36,000 should be expensed, with $36,000 remaining in prepaid expense. On October 1, the company paid $24,000 for property taxes for the one year period from October 1 to September 30, Year 2. By December 31, 3 months (October, November, and December) have expired and should be expensed. $24,000 / 12 months = $2,000 per month; therefore, $2,000 x 3 months = $6,000 should be expensed and $24,000 — 6,000 = $18,000 remains in prepaid expense. Total prepaid expenses on December 31, Year 1 = $36,000 + $18,000 = $54,000. Date Action From To Insur Taxes Total Coverage Period Prepaid Expenses 7/1/ear1 Payment 7/1/Year1 6/30/Year2 72 72 10/1/Year1 Payment 10/1/Year 9/30/Year 2 24 24 1 12/31/Year Amortize 7/1/Year1 12/31/Year (36) (36) 1 1 12/31/Year Amortize 10/1/Year 12/31/Year (6) (6) 1 4 1 wo fon) = fo) a aS 12/31/Year Balances 1 Choice \"A\" Is incorrect. This answer choice counts the entire amount of $24,000 in real estate taxes as prepaid expenses and only $24,000 (1/3) of the fire insurance premium. $6,000 of the real estate taxes paid should be expensed, and $36,000 (1/2) of the fire insurance premium should be expensed. Even though the insurance is for a 3-year period, the $72,000 is an annual premium and covers a period which encompasses half of Year 1 and half of Year 2. Choice \"B\" is incorrect. This answer choice includes the entire $24,000 in real estate taxes as prepaid expenses. $6,000 of the $24,000 should be expensed because it covered 3 months of Year 1 (Oct. 1—Dec. 31, Year 1). Choice \"D\" is incorrect. This answer choice excludes the real estate taxes in full. $6,000 of the $24,000 should be expensed, with $18,000 as prepaid expenses."
