      topic: "Diluted EPS",
      q: "Jones Corp.'s capital structure was as follows: December 31 Year 1 Year 2 Outstanding shares of stock: Common 110,000 110,000 Convertible preferred 10,000 10,000 8% convertible bonds $1,000,000 $1,000,000 During Year 2, Jones fully paid the required dividends of $3.00 per share on its preferred stock. The preferred shares are convertible into 20,000 shares of common stock. The 8% bonds are convertible into 30,000 shares of common stock. Net income for Year 2 is $850,000. Assume that the income tax rate is 30%. The diluted earnings per share for Year 2 is:",
      choices: ["$4.66", "$5.66", "$5.81", "$6.47"],
      answer: 1,
      explain: "Choice \"B\" is correct. $5.66 diluted EPS. Rule: All potentially dilutive convertible bonds and preferred stock are used in computing diluted EPS, using the \"as-if converted\" methodology required by GAAP. This means all dilutive securities are treated as if they were converted at the beginning of the year. Step 1: Test for dilution First, test for dilution by calculating basic EPS and checking the effects of the convertible securities against it. (Net income — Preferred dividends) Basic EPS Weighted average common shares outstanding $850,000 — ($3.00 per share x $10,000) 110,000 $7.45 per share (rounded) There is no need to calculate the weighted average shares of common stock, as there were no changes during the period. There were 110,000 shares during both years. Then we test for dilution by checking the effect on the numerator and denominator for EPS of each security against basic EPS: Convertible preferred stock $30,000 Preferred dividends saved if converted / 20,000 Shares of stock converted to common = $1.50. This is less than the basic EPS of $7.45, so the convertible preferred stock is dilutive. Convertible bonds The interest expense of $80,000 ($1,000,000 x 8%) would not be included in net income if the shares were converted, but we have to subtract that net of taxes ($80,000 x 30% Tax rate) since interest expense is deductible in arriving at net income: ($80,000 Interest — $24,000 Tax effect) / 30,000 Shares of common stock from the bond conversion = $1.87 (rounded). This is also less than basic EPS, so the bonds are dilutive. Step 2: Calculate diluted EPS Next, we calculate diluted EPS. Diluted EPS includes all potentially dilutive securities. We confirmed in step one that both the convertible preferred stock and the convertible bonds were dilutive, so we have both of those items to convert. The formula is: Diluted EPS = Adjusted net income / Adjusted shares outstanding Adjusted net income Start with net income and then adjust for the effects of the convertible securities: Net income $850,000 Add back: interest on convertible bonds ($1,000,000 x 8%) 80,000 Subtract: Tax effect of interest expense ($80,000 x 30%) (24,000) Adjusted net income $906,000 Note that the interest is added back because the bonds are assumed to be converted, meaning no interest is paid. The tax effect must be subtracted because interest is tax- deductible, and we lose the deduction, so taxes will increase. There is no \"adjustment\" for preferred dividends, because under the \"as-if converted\" rule, the company would not pay preferred dividends because the stock was treated as if it was converted at the beginning of the period. Essentially, we would subtract $0 for preferred dividends in the numerator. Adjusted shares outstanding Add the shares from the dilutive convertible securities to the common shares: Common shares 110,000 Add: shares from convertible preferred stock 20,000 Add: shares from convertible bonds 30,000 Adjusted shares outstanding $160,000 There is still no need to calculate weighted average share outstanding because the “as-if converted\" method means the conversion is treated as if it had occurred on the first period presented in the financial statements, meaning there would be no change throughout the year. Diluted EPS Diluted EPS = Adjusted net income / Adjusted shares outstanding = ($850,000 + 80,000 — 24,000) / 160,000 = $5.66 (rounded) Choice \"A\" is incorrect. This answer choice incorrectly subtracts interest instead of adding it: ($850,000 Net income — $80,000 Interest — $24,000 Tax effect) / (110,000 Shares common stock + 20,000 Shares preferred shares + 30,000 Bond shares) = $746,000 / 160,000 = $4.66. Choice \"C\" is incorrect. This answer choice incorrectly omits the tax effect of the interest expense for the convertible bonds: ($850,000 Net income + $80,000 Interest) / (110,000 Shares common stock + 20,000 Shares preferred shares + 30,000 Bond shares) = $930,000 / 160,000 = $5.81. Choice \"D\" is incorrect. This answer choice accounts for the interest and tax effect correctly but incorrectly omits the convertible preferred shares from the calculation: ($850,000 Net income + $80,000 Interest — $24,000 Tax effect) / (110,000 Shares common stock + 30,000 Bond shares) = $906,000 / 140,000 = $6.47."
